ategory:Donaldson Award winners]]\n[[Category:Honorary Golden Bear recipients]]\n[[Category:English-language film directors]]\n[[Category:Golden Globe Award-winning producers]]\n[[Category:Juilliard School alumni]]\n[[Category:Kennedy Center honorees]]\n[[Category:Ottoman emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Kayseri]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New Rochelle, New York]]\n[[Category:Tony Award winners]]\n[[Category:Williams College alumni]]\n[[Category:Yale School of Drama alumni]]\n[[Category:Male actors of Greek descent]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Writers from New Rochelle, New York]]\n[[Category:Film directors from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:Kazan family]]\n[[Category:Cappadocian Greeks]]\n", "name_user": "Mandruss", "label": "safe", "comment": "MOS:OVERLINK", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elia_Kazan"}
{"title_page": "Break of gauge", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=January 2016}}\n{{Sidebar track gauge}}\nWith railways, a '''break of gauge''' occurs where a line of one [[rail gauge|gauge]] meets a line of a different gauge: specifically a different [[track gauge]]. Trains and [[Railroad car|rolling stock]] cannot run through without some form of [[bogie exchange|conversion between gauges]], and [[Cargo|freight]] and [[passenger]]s must otherwise be [[Transloading|transshipped]]. A break of gauge adds delays, cost, and inconvenience.\n\n==Advantages and disadvantages==\n\n===Advantages===\n[[Image:Gauge changing in Brest, Belarus 08.jpg|thumb|right|[[Bogie exchange|Exchanging bogies]] at [[Brest, Belarus|Brest]] on the [[Belarus\u2013Poland border|Belarusian-Polish border]]]]\n* Narrow-gauge railways often have smaller [[loading gauge]]s and sharper curves, which tend to reduce initial [[capital cost]]s. These railways were often economically marginal lines, perhaps through hilly and mountainous terrain, where it would not have been economic to build a full-size railway. Many of these rail lines were operated independently of potentially connecting lines, as competing companies built and operated them. Thus the cost of transfer between different gauges was often irrelevant. Only the building of union stations or the nationalization of railroads changed this.\n*Invading armies may be severely hampered (as when Germany [[Operation Barbarossa|invaded]] the USSR in World War II). Spain (which had been invaded by [[Napoleon]]) deliberately maintained a wider gauge than France for this reason. This did not change until the beginning of the high-speed, standard-gauge [[AVE]] in 1992. The rest of the network continues to run on wide gauge.\n*If the railways also have different loading gauges, the break of track gauge might help prevent the larger wagons straying onto lines with smaller tunnels.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article70044948 |title=Tramway League. |newspaper=[[South Bourke and Mornington Journal]] |location=Richmond, Vic. |date=February 4, 1885 |accessdate=December 5, 2011 |page=3 Edition: Weekly. |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n*Similarly, if the larger and smaller gauges use different couplers or brakes, the break of gauge tends to keep the different couplers separate.\n\n====For passengers====\nFor passenger trains the inconvenience is less, especially at major stations where many passengers change trains or end their journeys anyway. Therefore, some passenger-only railways have been built with gauges not otherwise used in the country concerned. For example, the high-speed railways (and some [[rapid transit]] lines) in Japan and Spain use {{RailGauge|1435mm|lk=on}} while their respective mainline railroad systems use {{RailGauge|1067mm|lk=on}} and {{RailGauge|1668mm|lk=on}}.\n\nFor night trains, which are very common in countries such as Russia, the requirement to change trains is more inconvenient. In this case, often the [[bogie]]s are [[Bogie exchange|replaced]], even if it takes much more time than having passengers change trains.\n\n====For towns along the lines====\nIf local government has influence over the construction of railways, some may see it as desirable for trains (and passengers) to stop in rather than pass through their town. For instance, prior to the US Civil War, many cities in the South had a break of gauge or two separate stations at different ends of town, necessitating a change of trains or time-consuming transshipment, which nonetheless brought commerce and profit to the towns. Not until the Civil War did state and Confederate authorities notice the military and economic problems this brought, and only the post-bellum Union government was able to largely solve those problems, by converting almost all lines to standard gauge.\n\n==={{anchor|Inconvenience}}Disadvantages===\n[[File:Bogies-exchange.jpg|thumb|[[Bogie exchange|Exchanging bogies]] at [[Ussuriysk]] (near [[Vladivostok]]) on the Chinese&ndash;Russian border]]\n[[File:001015 gauge buster.jpg|thumb|A [[transporter wagon]]: one solution to the break-of-gauge problem]]\n\nTransshipping freight from cars of one gauge to cars of another is very labour- and time-intensive, and increases the risk of damage to goods. If the capacity of the freight cars on both systems does not match, additional inefficiencies can arise. If the frequency is low, a train might need to wait a long time for its counterpart to arrive before transshipping. This might be avoided by storing the goods, but that is also costly and inconvenient.\n\nTechnical solutions to avoid transshipping include [[Variable gauge|variable gauge axles]], replacing the [[bogie]]s of cars, and using transporter cars that can carry a car of a different gauge.\n\nThe Spanish manufacturers ''[[Talgo]]'' and ''[[Construcciones y Auxiliar de Ferrocarriles|CAF]]'' have developed dual-gauge axles ([[Variable gauge|variable gauge axles]]) which permit through running between broad-gauge and standard-gauge lines. In Japan the ''[[Gauge Change Train]]'', built on Talgo patents{{Citation needed|date=September 2009}}, runs on both standard and narrow {{RailGauge|1067mm}} gauge.\n\nBreaks-of-gauge might also be avoided by installing [[dual gauge|dual-gauge]] track, either permanently or as part of a project to replace one gauge with another.\n\nAt most breaks-of-gauge passengers have to change trains, but there are a few trains that run through, for example, the Talgo (variable-gauge axles, see above), and trains from Russia to China or Russia to Europe ([[bogie exchange]]), although on the latter two the passengers usually have to leave the train for some time whilst the accommodation work is done.\n\n====When buying trains====\nRailroads with unusual gauges or loading gauges have problems procuring trains, and may be forced to choose between an oligopoly or even a monopoly supplier that caters to their specific needs. This may be deliberate on the part of suppliers: some streetcar lines were built to unique specifications to ensure buyer lock-in. However, in modern times rail gauge itself is often not the most important factor, but rather other aspects like the electrification system or the loading gauge. Trains crossing the [[Channel Tunnel]], for instance, had to be custom made before [[High Speed 1]] was built, despite both Britain and France having standard gauge, because the British loading gauge is narrower and the legacy lines in the south of Britain were electrified through third rail rather than overhead wiring.\n\n==Overcoming a break of gauge==\n[[File:Break of gauge GWR Gloucester.jpg|thumb|A cartoon depicting the horrors of goods transfer at the break of gauge at Gloucester in 1843]]\n\nWhere trains encounter a different gauge, such as at the Spanish\u2013French border or the Russian\u2013Chinese one, the traditional solution has been [[transloading]] ([[transloading#Transloading versus transshipment|often called transshipment in discussions of break of gauge]]), that is, the transfer of passengers and freight to cars on the other system. When transloading from one gauge to another, often the quantities of rolling stock are unbalanced between the two systems, leading to more idle rolling stock on one system than the other. This is obviously far from optimal, and some other schemes have been devised.\n\nVarious solutions other than transloading were conceived even in the early era of railways in Britain<ref name=\"Rolt1989\">{{Harvnb|Rolt|1989}}.</ref>{{rp|202\u2013203}} (including [[rollbock]]s, [[transporter wagon]]s, [[dual gauge]], and even [[containerization]] or [[variable gauge]] axles), but they were not implemented during the nastiest flare-up of the [[Gauge War]] in the 1840s, which resulted in horrendous spectacles of confused and wasteful transloading.<ref name=\"Rolt1989\"/>{{rp|202\u2013203}} [[L. T. C. Rolt]]'s biography of [[Isambard Kingdom Brunel]] (mastermind of the broad gauge) remarks on the apparent mysteriousness of this lack of implementation,<ref name=\"Rolt1989\"/>{{rp|202\u2013203}} but a likely explanation is that the combatants at the time were more interested in winning the Gauge War, defeating the other gauge, than in demonstrating how peaceful coexistence could be developed. Rolt states that the shocking confusion seen in an [[editorial cartoon]] of transloading chaos at [[Gloucester]] in 1843 was deliberately [[wikt:contrived#Adjective|contrived]], as later admitted by a railway [[cargo|goods]] manager, as a [[spectacle]] for a visiting parliamentary committee.<ref name=\"Rolt1989\"/>{{rp|202\u2013203}} Rolt states that the germ of the idea of [[containerization]] was known even at this time,<ref name=\"Rolt1989\"/>{{rp|202\u2013203}} which is interesting in that the full potential of containerization was not thoroughly developed until a century later, after [[World War II]].\n\nLack of a standard gauge was a significant problem in transportation in the [[Confederate States of America]] during the [[American Civil War]].\n\n===Bogie exchange and variable gauge===\n{{main|Bogie exchange|Variable gauge}}\nOne common method to avoid transshipment is to build cars to the smaller of the two systems' [[loading gauge]]s with bogies that are easily removed and replaced with other bogies at an [[Bogie exchange|interchange]] location on the border. This takes a few minutes per car, but is quicker than [[Transloading#Transloading facilities|transshipment]] of goods.\n\nA more modern and sophisticated method is to have multigauge bogies whose wheels can be [[Variable gauge|moved inward and outward]]. Normally they are locked in place, but special equipment at the border unlocks the wheels and pushes them inward or outward to the new gauge, relocking the wheels when done. This can be done as the train moves slowly over special equipment.\n\n===Dual gauge and track gauge conversion===\n{{main|Dual gauge|Track gauge conversion}}\nIn some cases, breaks of gauge are avoided by installing dual-gauge track, either permanently or as part of a [[Track gauge conversion|changeover process]] to a single gauge.\n\n===Piggyback operation===\n{{main|Rollbock|Transporter wagon}}\nOne method of achieving interoperability between [[rolling stock]] of different gauges is to [[Piggyback (transportation)#Rail|piggyback]] stock of one gauge on special transporter wagons or even ordinary flat wagons fitted with rails. This enables rolling stock to reach workshops and other lines of the same gauge to which they are not otherwise connected. [[Transporter wagon|Piggyback]] operation by the trainload occurred as a temporary measure between [[Port Augusta railway station|Port Augusta]] and [[Marree railway station|Marree]] during [[gauge conversion]] work in the 1950s to bypass steep gradients and [[washaways]] in the [[Flinders Ranges]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southaustralianhistory.com.au/railways.htm|title=Piggyback picture}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southaustralianhistory.com.au/company.htm|title=FLINDERS RANGES RESEARCH}}</ref>\n\nNarrow-gauge railways were favoured in the underground slate quarries of [[North Wales]], as tunnels could be smaller. The [[Padarn Railway]] operated transporter wagons on their {{RailGauge|4ft|lk=on}} gauge railway, each carrying four {{RailGauge|1ft10.75in}} slate trams. When the [[Great Western Railway]] acquired one of the narrow-gauge lines in [[Blaenau Ffestiniog]], it deployed a similar type of transporter wagon to allow continued use of the quarries' existing slate wagons.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Gray |first=Adrian |date= Winter 1994 |title=G. W. R. Slate Tram Transporter Wagons |journal=British Railway Journal |issue=50 |pages=17\u201324}}</ref>\n\nTransporter wagons are most commonly used to transport narrow-gauge stock along standard-gauge lines.\n\nAt the [[Guinness brewery]] in [[Dublin]] there used to be {{RailGauge|1ft10in}} internal narrow gauge and {{RailGauge|5ft3in|lk=on}} gauge (standard gauge for Ireland), and to avoid the need for steam locomotives of both gauges the narrow-gauge engines were provided with standard-gauge converter wagons (named \"haulage trucks\"). The narrow-gauge steam locomotive was lowered into the haulage truck using a gantry, and its wheels rested on rollers, which in turn drove the haulage wagon wheels via a 3:1 reduction gear. Several of these locomotives survived into preservation, including locomotive No23 complete with haulage wagon and lifting gantry preserved at Brockham museum in 1966, and now at the [[Amberley Museum Railway]].\n\nMore rarely, standard-gauge vehicles are carried over narrow-gauge tracks using adaptor vehicles; examples include the [[Rollbock]]e transporter wagon arrangements in Germany, Austria, and the Czech Republic, and the milk transporter wagons of the [[Leek and Manifold Valley Light Railway]] in England.\n\n{{As of|2010}}, Japan is developing the [[Train on Train]] piggyback concept.\n\n===Containerisation===\n{{Main|Containerisation}} \nThe widespread use of [[Intermodal container#Rail|containers]] since the 1960s has made break of gauge less of a problem, since containers are efficiently transferred from one mode to another by suitable large [[Container crane|cranes]].\n\nIt helps if the lengths of the wagons on each gauge are the same so the containers can be transferred from one train to the other with no longitudinal movement along the trains. The different wagons should carry the same number of containers. Delays to each train depends on how many cranes can operate simultaneously.\n\nContainer cranes are relatively portable, so that if the break of gauge transshipment hub changes from time to time, the cranes can be moved around as required. [[Fork lift]] trucks can also be used.\n\nIt has been reported that, for example, when containers are shipped by a \"direct train\" from China to Europe, it is only containers, and not the railcars, which move from China's railway network to that of Kazakhstan. At the border station at [[Khorgos]], two trains (the Chinese {{RailGauge|sg|allk=on|disp=or}} one and the Kazakh {{RailGauge|1520mm|lk=on|disp=or}} one) would stand side by side at parallel tracks, while the cranes would move the containers from one train to the other in as short a time as 47 minutes.<ref name=forbes2016>{{cite|\nurl=https://www.forbes.com/sites/wadeshepard/2016/01/28/why-china-europe-silk-road-rail-transport-is-growing-fast\n|date=2016-01-28\n|title=Why The China-Europe 'Silk Road' Rail Network Is Growing Fast\n|first=Wade |last=Shepard \n|periodical=Forbes \n}}</ref>\n\n==Types==\n===Minor breaks of gauge===\nWherever there are narrow-gauge lines that connect with a standard-gauge line, there is technically a break of gauge. If the amount of traffic transferred between lines is small, this might be a small inconvenience only. In Austria and Switzerland there are numerous breaks-of-gauge between standard-gauge main lines and narrow-gauge railways.\n\nMany internal Swiss railways that operate in the more mountainous regions are {{RailGauge|1000mm|allk=on}}, and most are equipped with [[rack railway|rack]] assistance to deal with the relatively steep gradients encountered.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bueker.net/trainspotting/map.php?file=maps/switzerland/switzerland.gif|accessdate=2011-02-19|title=enlarged map}}</ref> Through running of standard-gauge trains on rack sections would not be possible, but dual-gauge track exists in many places where the gradient is relatively flat to carry standard- and metre-gauge stock. There are also some 800-mm-gauge railways which are entirely rack operated.\n\nThe effects of a minor break of gauge can be minimized by placing it at the point where a cargo must be removed from cars anyway. An example of this is the [[East Broad Top Railroad]] in the US, which had a [[coal breaker|coal wash and preparation plant]] at its break of gauge in [[Mount Union, Pennsylvania]]. The coal was unloaded from narrow-gauge cars of the EBTR, and after processing was loaded into standard-gauge cars of the [[Pennsylvania Railroad]].\n\n=== Nominal breaks of gauge ===\nThe line between Finland and Russia has a nominal break of gauge; Finnish gauge is {{RailGauge|1524mm|lk=on}} whereas [[Russian gauge]] is {{RailGauge|1520mm|lk=on}}. This does not usually prevent through-running, and in fact, such a service exists in the form of the [[Allegro (train)|Allegro]] high-speed service between Helsinki and St. Petersburg. The nominal {{convert|4|mm|abbr=on}} difference is generally within tolerance, and the present Russian gauge is actually a redefinition of the older {{RailGauge|1524mm}}.\n\nThe [[Iberian gauge]] is actually three slightly different gauges: {{RailGauge|1672mm}} in Spain, {{RailGauge|1664mm}} in Portugal, and the newer, redefined {{RailGauge|1668mm|lk=on}}. Through-running is done with vehicles having a gauge within certain tolerances. [[Indian gauge]], {{RailGauge|1676mm|lk=on}}, is also compatible with Iberian gauge, although there are no actual railway connections between the two. Despite this, old Spanish and Portuguese rolling stock have been reused in Argentina and Chile, both of which use Indian gauge.\n\nA nominal break of gauge with [[standard gauge]] exists as well: on the Hong Kong [[MTR]] network, lines owned by [[MTR Corporation]] use {{RailGauge|1432mm|lk=on}} rather than the {{RailGauge|1435mm}} employed on those owned by [[Kowloon-Canton Railway Corporation|KCR Corporation]], despite the lack of physical connections between the two networks.\n\n=== Other types of breaks ===\nA large railway may have main lines with heavy tracks, and branch lines with light track. Light locomotives and rolling stock can operate on all lines, but heavy locomotives and rolling stock can only operate on heavy track.  Heavy rolling stock might be able to operate on lighter track at reduced speed.  Light track can be upgraded to heavy track by installing heavy rails, etc., and this can be done without changing the track gauge.\n\n==Gauge conversions==\n{{Main|Track gauge conversion}}\n\n===Gauge orphan===\nWhen a main line is converted to a different gauge, branch lines can be cut off and made relatively useless, at least for freight trains, until they too are converted to the new gauge. These severed branches can be called '''gauge orphans'''.\n\n===Gauge outreach===\nThe opposite of a gauge orphan is a line of one gauge which reaches into the territory composed mainly of another gauge. Examples include five broad-gauge lines from Victoria, Australia, which crossed the border into otherwise standard-gauge New South Wales. Similarly, the standard-gauge line from Albury to Melbourne in 1962 which eliminated most transshipment at Albury, especially the need for passengers to change trains in the middle of the night.\n\nTwo Russian broad-gauge lines reach out from Ukraine, one (the [[Uzhhorod\u2013Ko\u0161ice broad-gauge track|Uzhhorod\u2013Ko\u0161ice line]]) into Slovakia to carry minerals; another (the [[Broad Gauge Metallurgy Line|Metallurgy Line]]) into Poland to carry heavy iron ore and steel products without the need for transshipment as would be the case if there were a break of gauge at the border. There are plans to extend the Slovak line to Vienna.<ref name=broad-gauge-to-wien-2010/>\n\nIn 1994, the [[Rail Baltica]] proposal emerged to build a 728&nbsp;km north\u2013south line to link European standard-gauge railways from Poland to [[Kaunas]], Lithuania, and via [[Riga]], Latvia, to [[Tallinn]], Estonia.<ref>[[Railway Gazette International]] July 2011, p 25.</ref> In the shorter term (the 2010s) it will only be built to Kaunas.\n\nThe gauge outreach from [[Kalgoorlie]] to [[Perth]] partly replaced the original narrow-gauge line, and partly rebuilt that line with better curves and gradients as double-track dual gauge. Because of lack of space at the main Perth station, standard-gauge passenger trains terminate one station short at [[East Perth railway station|East Perth]].\n\n==Other issues==\nWhile track gauge is the most important factor preventing through running between adjacent systems, other issues can also be a hindrance, including [[structure gauge]], [[loading gauge]], [[axleload]]s, [[Railway coupling|couplings]], [[Railway brake#Air versus vacuum brakes|brakes]], [[railway electrification system|electrification systems]], [[railway signal|signalling]] systems, [[multiple unit]] controls, [[Safeworking|rules and regulations]], driver certification, righthand or lefthand running, repairs (how to make and pay for repairs while rolling stock is on other railway's territory) and language. The structure gauge, loading gauge and axleload problems are solved by simply using the smaller options for through running. The general solution is often to custom-build vehicles to fit all the standards to be encountered. Trains can be built to accept four voltages, to have dual signaling systems equipment, etc. All of these solutions, however, usually result in either more expensive trains or less comfort for passengers (e.g. through less room inside the train if it has a smaller loading gauge) or \u2013 in the case of freight railways \u2013 less room for cargo, making [[double-stack rail transport|double stacking]] impossible or other negative effects.\n\n==Examples==\n\n===Europe===\n\n==== United Kingdom ====\n* [[Gloucester]] was the earliest significant break of gauge between the {{RailGauge|1435mm}} and {{RailGauge|7ft0.25in|lk=on}} systems.\n* 1864 \u2013 [[Southern Railway routes west of Salisbury#Break of Gauge|Yeovil]]\n\n====Russian gauge meeting western gauge====\n[[File:Bogie change station at Chop station Ukraine.jpg|thumb|Bogie-exchange station in Ukraine]]\n* [[Poland]], [[Slovakia]], [[Hungary]] and [[Romania]] ({{RailGauge|1435mm}}).\n:vs. Former Soviet Union countries: Russia, [[Lithuania]], [[Belarus]], [[Ukraine]],  [[Moldova]] ({{RailGauge|1520mm}}). Night trains are common, and they are often [[Bogie exchange|bogie-exchanged]].\n*Finland ({{RailGauge|1524mm}}) and Sweden ({{RailGauge|1435mm}}), between [[Tornio]] and [[Haparanda]] via a short [[dual gauge]] bridge. Freight is generally [[Transloading#Transloading facilities|transloaded]]. No passenger trains. There is also a [[SeaRail]] [[train ferry]] (with {{RailGauge|1435mm}} onboard) linking [[Turku]], Finland with [[Stockholm]], Sweden;<ref>[http://www.searail.net/en/index.html SeaRail ferry] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091226152232/http://www.searail.net/en/index.html |date=December 26, 2009 }}. Retrieved 2010-03-18</ref> the Turku terminal handles [[Dual gauge|both gauges]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.searail.net/en/services/collection_distribution.html|title=SeaRail Turku dual-gauge terminal|access-date=March 18, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724060053/http://www.searail.net/en/services/collection_distribution.html|archive-date=July 24, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*[[Bulgaria]] ({{RailGauge|1435mm}}) [[Train ferry|railroad ferries]] to Ukraine, Russia and [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] ({{RailGauge|1520mm}})\n*Germany ({{RailGauge|1435mm}}) railroad ferries (from Sassnitz with {{RailGauge|1520mm}} onboard) to Russia and Baltic States and to Finland (also from Travem\u00fcnde with {{RailGauge|1435mm}} onboard).\n*[[Turkey]] and [[Iran]] vs [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]], [[Armenia]], [[Azerbaijan]], [[Turkmenistan]]\n*While breaks of gauge are generally located near borders, the [[Uzhhorod \u2013 Ko\u0161ice broad gauge track|Uzhhorod \u2013 Ko\u0161ice line]] carrying iron ore from Ukraine extends into Slovakian territory to a steelworks near [[Ko\u0161ice]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sinfin.net/railways/world/slovakia.html|title=Railways in Slovakia}}</ref> and there are plans to extend the line further west, to [[Vienna]].<ref name=broad-gauge-to-wien-2010>{{cite web|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/nc/news/single-view/view/broad-gauge-to-wien-is-feasible-says-study.html|accessdate=2010-12-21|title=Railway Gazette: Broad gauge to Wien is feasible, says study}}</ref> See also [[Rail gauge in Slovakia]].\n*The historically first break of gauge between Russian and standard gauge was built in 1861 as dual gauge between the border stations of Eydtkuhnen, Germany (now [[Chernyshevskoye]] [[Kaliningrad Oblast]], Russia), and [[Kybartai]], then Russia, now Lithuania.\n* The 1520 Strategic Partnership seeks to harmonise the gauges of Europe-Asia.<ref>[[Railway Gazette International]] Oct 2011 p48</ref>\n\n====Iberian gauge meeting western gauge====\n*France ({{RailGauge|1435mm|disp=or}}) and Spain ({{RailGauge|1668mm|disp=or}}), for example at [[Cerb\u00e8re]] (FR) \u2013 [[Portbou]] (ES); [[Hendaye]] (FR) \u2013 [[Irun]] (ES) and [[Latour-de-Carol]]. From 2010 the [[:Category:High-speed railway lines in Spain|Spanish high-speed network]] ({{RailGauge|1435mm|disp=or}}) is connected to the French railways without a break of gauge.\n[[File:Talgo Variable Gauge Axle.jpg|thumb|[[Variable gauge axle]]s as fitted to a Spanish train designed for intercity travel to France]]\nThe earliest working example of the [[axle changing system|axle-changing system]] at the French-Spain border in 1948 had the [[axle]]s being changed at the rate of 8 wagons or 32 axles per hour.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article48647650 |title=BREAK OF GAUGE DEVICE PLEASES. |newspaper=[[The Barrier Miner]] |location=Broken Hill, NSW |date=July 16, 1951 |accessdate=November 3, 2011 |page=5 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n====Local narrow-gauge lines meeting mainlines====\n*Switzerland, see \"[[Break of gauge#Minor breaks of gauge|Minor breaks of gauge]]\" section below.\n*The Harzer Schmalspurbahn took over a standard-gauge line from Deutsche Bahn when the latter had no more use for it and regauged it to meter gauge to prevent the problems of break of gauge. Nonetheless a break of gauge (and a change of train operator) still occurs at the point where that line connects to the rest of the DB network. DB itself has no break of gauge problems as the only non-standard-gauge railway it operates is on the island of Wangerooge without any train connection to the mainland.\n\n=== North America ===\nThe [[Track gauge in the United States|United States of America]] had broad-, narrow-, and standard-gauge tracks in the 19th century, but is now almost entirely {{RailGauge|1435mm}} standard gauge. [[Narrow gauge railroads in the United States|Narrow-gauge operations]] are generally confined to isolated rail systems, with a few notable exceptions.\n*{{flagicon|Guatemala}} {{flagicon|Mexico}} A break of gauge, {{RailGauge|3ft}} to {{RailGauge|ussg}}, between [[Rail transport in Guatemala|Guatemala]] and [[Rail transport in Mexico|Mexico]] is currently closed.\n*{{flagicon|USA}} In [[Antonito, Colorado]], there is a break between the standard-gauge [[Rio Grande Scenic Railroad]] and the narrow-gauge [[Cumbres and Toltec Scenic Railroad]], billed as the [https://web.archive.org/web/20091219152629/http://www.riograndescenicrailroad.com/Tickets-and-Train-Schedules/Tickets-Routes-and-Schedules.html#tg Toltec Gorge Limited].\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[BART]] in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]] has a [[cross-platform interchange]] between the electrified {{Railgauge|1,676 mm}} broad-gauge [[Antioch\u2013SFO/Millbrae line]] and non-electrified standard gauge [[eBART]] at a transfer platform east of [[Pittsburg/Bay Point station]]. The eBART system is designed to allow the new trackage to be electrified and regauged for BART mainline trains at a later date.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gary Richards|first1=Gary Richards|title=Roadshow: eBART trains along Highway 4 could be running in 2017|url=http://www.contracostatimes.com/mr-roadshow/ci_25479165/roadshow-ebart-trains-along-highway-4-could-be|accessdate=February 24, 2015|work=Contra Costa Times|publisher=MNG Corporate|date=April 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===South America===\n*Argentina and Chile both use {{RailGauge|1676mm}} broad-gauge tracks, but [[Transandine Railway|the link railway]] uses {{RailGauge|1000mm}} narrow gauge with [[rack railway]] sections. There are two break-of-gauge stations, one at [[Los Andes, Chile]], and the other at [[Mendoza, Argentina]].\n*A break of gauge between [[Transportation in Argentina|Argentina]] and [[Transportation in Brazil|Brazil]], {{RailGauge|1435mm}} to {{RailGauge|1000mm}}\n*A break of gauge between [[Transport in Uruguay|Uruguay]] and Brazil, {{RailGauge|1435mm}} to {{RailGauge|1000mm}} at [[Santana do Livramento]].\n[[File:China - Russia Railway.jpg|thumb|A train crossing the [[China\u2013Russia border|Chinese&ndash;Russian border]], with a bogie-exchange station visible on the Russian side in the background]]\n\n===Asia===\n====China====\n[[Rail transport in China|China]] has a standard-gauge network; neighbouring countries [[Rail transport in Mongolia|Mongolia]], [[Rail transport in Russia|Russia]] and [[Qazaqstan Temir Zholy|Kazakhstan]] use {{RailGauge|1520mm}} gauge, and [[Vietnam]] mostly uses {{RailGauge|1000mm}} ([[metre gauge]]), so there are some breaks of gauge. See the [[Trans-Manchurian Railway]] (gauge changing at [[Zabaikalsk]] on the Russian side of the border), the [[Trans-Mongolian Railway]] and the [[Lanxin railway]]. The [[Yunnan\u2013Vietnam Railway]] is narrow gauge, and is connected to standard-gauge tracks both in [[Kunming]] and in [[Hekou North Railway Station|Hekou]].<ref name=\"luhao20150424\">{{cite|url=http://www.peoplerail.com/rail/show-456-224377-1.html\n|title=\u6606\u660e\u94c1\u8def\u5c40\uff1a\u56fd\u9645\u94c1\u8def\u8054\u8fd0\u5f00\u542f\u4e91\u5357\u8d27\u8fd0\u65b0\u7bc7\u7ae0 (Kunming Railway Bureau: An international railway link opens a new chapter in Yunnan's freigh transportation)\n|date=2015-04-24|last=Lu |first=Hua (\u9646\u534e)|last2=Guo|first2=Weina (\u90ed\u8587\u5a1c)}}</ref>\nThe [[Nanning]]-[[Hanoi]] line is dual gauge in Vietnam as far as Hanoi.<ref>[http://www.vr.com.vn/english/hientaihoatdong.html The length of Vietnam railway network] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100418132723/http://www.vr.com.vn/english/hientaihoatdong.html |date=April 18, 2010 }}</ref> There is currently a break of gauge at [[Dostyk]] on the Kazakh border. Kazakhstan was planning to build an additional line using standard gauge,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view/trans-kazakhstan-link-will-complete-standard-gauge-transcontinental-artery/browse/4.html\n|date=August 1, 2004 |accessdate=April 28, 2011\n|work=Railway Gazette |title=Trans-Kazakhstan link will complete standard-gauge transcontinental artery\n}}</ref> between Dostyk and [[Aktogay, East Kazakhstan Province|Aktogay]] but the scheme was abandoned.\n\n====Iran====\n[[Rail transport in Iran|Iran]], with its standard-gauge rail system, has a break of gauge with {{RailGauge|1520mm}} gauge at the borders with [[Azerbaijan]] and [[Turkmenistan]], and also with [[Rail transport in Pakistan|Pakistan's]] {{RailGauge|5ft6in}} [[Indian gauge]] at [[Zahedan]]. The break-of-gauge station at Zahedan was built outside the city, as the existing station was hemmed in by built-up areas.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/nc/news/single-view/view/closing-the-gap-from-bam-to-zahedan.html| title=Closing the gap from Bam to Zahedan| work=[[Railway Gazette International]]| first=John| last=Stubbs| date=January 1, 2007| accessdate=May 26, 2011 }}</ref>\n[[File:Free Gauge Train GCT-01 at kamogawa.jpg|thumb|The first-generation, experimental [[Gauge Change Train]] as seen in 2003]]\n\n====Japan====\nAll high-speed \"[[Shinkansen]]\" routes in Japan have been built as standard-gauge lines. A few routes, known as \"[[Super Tokky\u016b]]\", have been planned as narrow-gauge {{RailGauge|3ft6in}}, and the conventional (non-high-speed) is mostly narrow-gauge {{RailGauge|3ft6in}}, so there are some breaks of gauge and dual gauge is used in some places. Private railways often use other gauges.\n\nWhile most of the Japanese urban rail/metro lines use {{RailGauge|1067mm}} rail gauge, a considerable number of lines (including all lines of the [[Osaka Metro]]) are still using their own different gauges including {{RailGauge|762mm}}, {{RailGauge|1372mm}}, and {{RailGauge|1435mm}}.<ref>http://www.jterc.or.jp/topics/josei_shinpo3.14/5_chokutu_unten.pdf</ref> This prevented the creation of some [[through train]] services.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sc.city.kawasaki.jp/faq/contents_detail.php?frmId=12992|title=\u5ddd\u5d0e\u5e02\uff1a\u30da\u30fc\u30b8\u304c\u898b\u3064\u304b\u308a\u307e\u305b\u3093|website=sc.city.kawasaki.jp}}{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, [[Hokkaido Railway Company]] (JR Hokkaido) started working on a transporter train by trainload concept called \"[[Train on Train]]\" to carry narrow-gauge freight trains at faster speeds on standard-gauge flatcars. The [[Seikan Tunnel]] has beien converted by JR Hokkaido to dual gauge to accommodate the [[Hokkaido Shinkansen]].\n\nAn experimental variable gauge \"[[Gauge Change Train]]\" has also been tested since 1998 as a means to allow through services from high-speed standard-gauge Shinkansen lines to narrow-gauge regional lines. Its first deployment is expected to be [[Kyushu Shinkansen]] Nagasaki route.\n\n====North Korea====\nThe [[Rail transport in North Korea|North Korea]]n rail system has some breaks of gauge. Several parts of the [[Paektusan Ch'\u014fngny\u014fn Line]] on the stretch between Wiy\u014fn and Hyesan Ch'\u014fngny\u014fn are dual gauged to allow connections to the [[Paektusan Rimch'\u014fl Line]] and the [[Samjiy\u014fn Line]].<ref>http://www.cybernk.net/infoText/InfoHumanCultureDetail.aspx?mc=CC0501&sc=A33005001&tid=CC040100007874&direct=1&direct=1</ref> Also, the line connecting to the [[Trans-Siberian Railway]] from Rajin to Khasan is dual gauged for standard gauge and Russian gauge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=100&oid=112&aid=0002232229|title=\ub77c\uc9c4-\ud558\uc0b0(\ub7ec\uc2dc\uc544) \ucca0\ub3c4, 10\uc6d4 \uc911\uc21c \uccab \uc2dc\ud5d8\uc6b4\ud589|publisher=news.naver.com}}</ref>\n\n====Sakhalin====\nIn the 20th century, railroads on the entire Sakhalin used the same {{RailGauge|3ft6in}} narrow gauge as Japan, as part of it was under Japan's control when railway construction began.  One stretch of rail that used {{RailGauge|600mm}} narrow gauge was converted to match the {{RailGauge|3ft6in}} narrow gauge after Russia took control of it.\n\nStarting from the 1970s, a train ferry service was provided to connect Sakhalin and the Russia mainland, requiring bogie exchange on wagons to allow operation on the Russian mainland {{RailGauge|1520mm}} broad gauge.\n\nIn 2003, the Russian government started to convert the entire network to dual gauge with {{RailGauge|3ft6in}} and {{RailGauge|1520mm}}. Work is 70% done as of 2016, and is expected to be complete by 2018. The entire island's rolling stock is expected to be replaced by {{RailGauge|1520mm}} rolling stock by 2020, thus eliminating the break of gauge between Sakhalin and the Russian mainland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interfax-russia.ru/FarEast/news.asp?id=730322&sec=1671|title=\u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 - \u0414\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0444\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043e\u043a\u0440\u0443\u0433 -  interfax-russia.ru|website=www.interfax-russia.ru}}</ref>\n\n==== Taiwan ====\n[[File:Taiwan Railways Route Map 201301.svg|thumb|Route of THSR shown in orange; all others are operated by TRA, Taiwan]]\n\nLike Japan, [[rail transport in Taiwan]] uses the {{RailGauge|3ft6in}} gauge for the majority of its railway network, but {{RailGauge|sg}} standard gauge for its high-speed rail; however, gauge differences are less of a problem as [[Taiwan High Speed Rail]] generally uses separate rolling stocks and its own discrete railway, and at most locations runs on routes kilometres away from the conventional [[Taiwan Railways Administration]] railway network.\n\n===Africa===\n* Rail lines linked by ferries on convenient rivers or lakes. See [[Train ferry|train ferries]].\n* [[Dar es Salaam]] is one of the few places in Africa where different gauges actually meet.\n* [[Kidatu]] in [[Tanzania]] has a container transshipment facility to move freight containers between [[TAZARA Railway|TAZARA]] {{RailGauge|1067mm}} and [[Tanzania Railways Corporation]] trains {{RailGauge|1000mm}}\n* [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|D. R. Congo]] originally had both {{RailGauge|1000mm}} and {{RailGauge|3ft6in}} lines, but when these lines met in the 1950s, the {{RailGauge|1000mm}} line was converted to {{RailGauge|3ft6in}}.\n* In the rest of Africa, railways of different gauges in adjacent countries often do not actually meet, so there is no actual break of gauge.\n\n===Oceania===\n\n====Australia====\n[[File:AlburyRailwayStationPlatform.jpg|thumb|The break-of-gauge platform for the [[Sydney\u2013Melbourne railway]] at [[Albury railway station|Albury station]]; [[Standard gauge|SG]] on left; [[Broad gauge|BG]] on right.]]\n\n===== Origins =====\n\n* (1845) Evils of break of gauge and [[Royal Commission on Railway Gauges|Gauge Commission]] of UK mentioned in a South Australian newspaper.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71603492 |title=The Proposed Railroad. |newspaper=[[The South Australian]] |location=Adelaide |date=December 12, 1845 |accessdate=November 28, 2011 |page=3 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nThe then two mainland colonies originally agreed to adopt the {{RailGauge|impsg}} gauge.\n\n* [[South Australia]] (1847)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71609590 |title=Proceedings of the Legisaltive Council. |newspaper=[[The South Australian]] |location=Adelaide |date=October 8, 1847 |accessdate=November 26, 2011 |page=3 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article59769848 |title=Local Intelligence. |newspaper=[[Bell's Life in Sydney and Sporting Reviewer]] |date=December 1, 1849 |accessdate=November 27, 2011 |page=2 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n* [[New South Wales]] (1848)<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/>\n\nHowever, in 1850 New South Wales decided to change to the {{RailGauge|63in}}, or [[Irish gauge]]. The change was approved by the British government, and South Australia agreed to follow suit.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article38441575 |title=Railway Papers. |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=August 28, 1851 |accessdate=November 27, 2011 |page=3 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> However, in 1853 New South Wales unilaterally reverted to the {{RailGauge|impsg}} gauge. South Australia and [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], the latter now separated from New South Wales, protested about the broken agreement, to no avail.\n\n===== Current =====\n*[[Queensland]] ({{RailGauge|3ft6in}}) and [[New South Wales]] ({{RailGauge|impsg|disp=or}})\n*New South Wales ({{RailGauge|impsg|disp=or}}) and [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] ({{RailGauge|63in|disp=or}})\n*Southern [[South Australia]] uses broad gauge, like Victoria. Northern South Australia and southern South Australia had a number of [[narrow gauge railway|narrow-gauge]] {{RailGauge|3ft6in}} lines, leading to several break-of-gauge stations at various times including [[Hamley Bridge]], [[Terowie railway station|Terowie]], [[Peterborough railway station, South Australia|Peterborough]], [[Gladstone railway station, South Australia|Gladstone]], [[Port Pirie Junction railway station|Port Pirie Junction]], [[Port Pirie (Mary Elie Street) railway station|Port Pirie Mary Elie Street]], [[Port Augusta railway station|Port Augusta]], [[Marree railway station|Marree]], [[Wolseley, South Australia|Wolseley]] and [[Mount Gambier railway station|Mount Gambier]]. The [[Eyre Peninsula Railway]] lines have always been isolated.\n*In the latter part of the 20th century, all mainland capital cities were connected by a standard-gauge {{RailGauge|impsg}} network, leading to more breaks of gauge (or branch line closures) in states where this is not the norm\n*[[Perth]]'s railway system is narrow gauge ({{RailGauge|3ft6in|disp=or}}), while the ''[[Indian Pacific]]'' is standard gauge. The line between [[East Perth railway station|East Perth]] and [[Midland railway station, Perth|Midland]], the eastern suburban terminus, and inland to the major rail junction at [[Northam, Western Australia|Northam]] is dual gauge]. All rail east of this is standard gauge.\n*Since the 1990s, new concrete sleepers installed in the [[Adelaide]] suburban area have been [[Track gauge conversion|gauge convertible]] \n*In May 2008, agreement reached to convert the declining trafficked broad-gauge line of a [[broad gauge|BG]]/[[standard gauge|SG]] pair for 200&nbsp;km between [[Seymour railway station|Seymour]] and [[Albury railway station|Albury]] to [[double track]] standard gauge for growing interstate traffic.\n*Since the 1930s, most Victoria steam locomotives were designed for ease of conversion to standard gauge, but except for [[Victorian Railways R class|R766]], this has never happened.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railpage.com.au/f-t11303096-s180-0-asc.htm |title=It's {{sic|Offi|cal|nolink=yes}} R766 to be gauge converted & head for N.S.W \u2013 Victoria \u2013 Forums \u2013 Railpage Australia |publisher=Railpage.com.au |accessdate=15 June 2012}}</ref>\n*Note that the lines of the same gauge do not all join up, being separated by other gauges, deserts, rivers, lakes or oceans. Rolling stock is often transferred on [[Lowboy (trailer)|low-loaders]], [[Train ferry|train ferries]], [[car float]]s or even by [[ship]].\n\n==== New Zealand ====\nNew Zealand originally had small lengths of lines of {{RailGauge|3ft6in}}, {{RailGauge|impsg}} and {{RailGauge|63in}}, but quickly converted all to {{RailGauge|3ft6in}}, which better suited the sparsely populated and mountainous country.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Trains}}\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Erie Gauge War]]\n* [[Eurasian Land Bridge]]\n* [[Gauntlet track]]\n* [[Janes World Railways]] has maps that generally show breaks-of-gauge.\n* [[Piggyback (transportation)]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southaustralianhistory.com.au/fees.htm|title=Flinders Ranges Research Fees}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southaustralianhistory.com.au/email.htm|title=Flinders Ranges Research Email}}</ref>\n* [[Ramsey car-transfer apparatus]]\n* [[Track gauge conversion]]\n* [[Variable gauge axles]]\n** [[INTERGAUGE]] a form of VGA\n** [[SUW 2000]] a form of VGA\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{ cite book\n  | first = L. T. C. |last=Rolt\n  | title = Isambard Kingdom Brunel\n  | year = 1989\n  | origyear = 1957\n  | publisher = Prentice Hall Press\n  | isbn = 978-0-582-10744-1\n  | ref = harv\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061205185702/http://jwr.janes.com/public/jwr/index.shtml Jane's World Railways] (hard copy)\n*Transport and Telecommunication:[http://www.tsi.lv/Transport&Telecommunication/v71_en/art15.pdf The operation of the gauge changing facility of the new railway line Rail Baltica]{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, Jonas Jonaitis, Vol.7, No 1, 2006\n\n{{Navbox track gauge}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2016}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Break Of Gauge}}\n[[Category:Track gauges]]\n\n[[es:Cambiador de ancho]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=January 2016}}\n{{Sidebar track gauge}}\nWith railways, a '''break of gauge''' occurs where a line of one [[rail gauge|gauge]] meets a line of a different gauge: specifically a different [[track gauge]]. Trains and [[Railroad car|rolling stock]] cannot run through without some form of [[bogie exchange|conversion between gauges]], and [[Cargo|freight]] and [[passenger]]s must otherwise be [[Transloading|transshipped]]. A break of gauge adds delays, cost, and inconvenience.\n\n==Advantages and disadvantages==\n\n===Advantages===\n[[Image:Gauge changing in Brest, Belarus 08.jpg|thumb|right|[[Bogie exchange|Exchanging bogies]] at [[Brest, Belarus|Brest]] on the [[Belarus\u2013Poland border|Belarusian-Polish border]]]]\n* Narrow-gauge railways often have smaller [[loading gauge]]s and sharper curves, which tend to reduce initial [[capital cost]]s. These railways were often economically marginal lines, perhaps through hilly and mountainous terrain, where it would not have been economic to build a full-size railway. Many of these rail lines were operated independently of potentially connecting lines, as competing companies built and operated them. Thus the cost of transfer between different gauges was often irrelevant. Only the building of union stations or the nationalization of railroads changed this.\n*Invading armies may be severely hampered (as when Germany [[Operation Barbarossa|invaded]] the USSR in World War II). Spain (which had been invaded by [[Napoleon]]) deliberately maintained a wider gauge than France for this reason. This did not change until the beginning of the high-speed, standard-gauge [[AVE]] in 1992. The rest of the network continues to run on wide gauge.\n*If the railways also have different loading gauges, the break of track gauge might help prevent the larger wagons straying onto lines with smaller tunnels.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article70044948 |title=Tramway League. |newspaper=[[South Bourke and Mornington Journal]] |location=Richmond, Vic. |date=February 4, 1885 |accessdate=December 5, 2011 |page=3 Edition: Weekly. |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n*Similarly, if the larger and smaller gauges use different couplers or brakes, the break of gauge tends to keep the different couplers separate.\n\n====For passengers====\nFor passenger trains the inconvenience is less, especially at major stations where many passengers change trains or end their journeys anyway. Therefore, some passenger-only railways have been built with gauges not otherwise used in the country concerned. For example, the high-speed railways (and some [[rapid transit]] lines) in Japan and Spain use {{RailGauge|1435mm|lk=on}} while their respective mainline railroad systems use {{RailGauge|1067mm|lk=on}} and {{RailGauge|1668mm|lk=on}}.\n\nFor night trains, which are very common in countries such as Russia, the requirement to change trains is more inconvenient. In this case, often the [[bogie]]s are [[Bogie exchange|replaced]], even if it takes much more time than having passengers change trains.\n\n====For towns along the lines====\nIf local government has influence over the construction of railways, some may see it as desirable for trains (and passengers) to stop in rather than pass through their town. For instance, prior to the US Civil War, many cities in the South had a break of gauge or two separate stations at different ends of town, necessitating a change of trains or time-consuming transshipment, which nonetheless brought commerce and profit to the towns. Not until the Civil War did state and Confederate authorities notice the military and economic problems this brought, and only the post-bellum Union government was able to largely solve those problems, by converting almost all lines to standard gauge.\n\n==={{anchor|Inconvenience}}Disadvantages===\n[[File:Bogies-exchange.jpg|thumb|[[Bogie exchange|Exchanging bogies]] at [[Ussuriysk]] (near [[Vladivostok]]) on the Chinese&ndash;Russian border]]\n[[File:001015 gauge buster.jpg|thumb|A [[transporter wagon]]: one solution to the break-of-gauge problem]]\n\nTransshipping freight from cars of one gauge to cars of another is very labour- and time-intensive, and increases the risk of damage to goods. If the capacity of the freight cars on both systems does not match, additional inefficiencies can arise. If the frequency is low, a train might need to wait a long time for its counterpart to arrive before transshipping. This might be avoided by storing the goods, but that is also costly and inconvenient.\n\nTechnical solutions to avoid transshipping include [[Variable gauge|variable gauge axles]], replacing the [[bogie]]s of cars, and using transporter cars that can carry a car of a different gauge.\n\nThe Spanish manufacturers ''[[Talgo]]'' and ''[[Construcciones y Auxiliar de Ferrocarriles|CAF]]'' have developed dual-gauge axles ([[Variable gauge|variable gauge axles]]) which permit through running between broad-gauge and standard-gauge lines. In Japan the ''[[Gauge Change Train]]'', built on Talgo patents{{Citation needed|date=September 2009}}, runs on both standard and narrow {{RailGauge|1067mm}} gauge.\n\nBreaks-of-gauge might also be avoided by installing [[dual gauge|dual-gauge]] track, either permanently or as part of a project to replace one gauge with another.\n\nAt most breaks-of-gauge passengers have to change trains, but there are a few trains that run through, for example, the Talgo (variable-gauge axles, see above), and trains from Russia to China or Russia to Europe ([[bogie exchange]]), although on the latter two the passengers usually have to leave the train for some time whilst the accommodation work is done.\n\n====When buying trains====\nRailroads with unusual gauges or loading gauges have problems procuring trains, and may be forced to choose between an oligopoly or even a monopoly supplier that caters to their specific needs. This may be deliberate on the part of suppliers: some streetcar lines were built to unique specifications to ensure buyer lock-in. However, in modern times rail gauge itself is often not the most important factor, but rather other aspects like the electrification system or the loading gauge. Trains crossing the [[Channel Tunnel]], for instance, had to be custom made before [[High Speed 1]] was built, despite both Britain and France having standard gauge, because the British loading gauge is narrower and the legacy lines in the south of Britain were electrified through third rail rather than overhead wiring.\n\n==Overcoming a break of gauge==\n[[File:Break of gauge GWR Gloucester.jpg|thumb|A cartoon depicting the horrors of goods transfer at the break of gauge at Gloucester in 1843]]\n\nWhere trains encounter a different gauge, such as at the Spanish\u2013French border or the Russian\u2013Chinese one, the traditional solution has been [[transloading]] ([[transloading#Transloading versus transshipment|often called transshipment in discussions of break of gauge]]), that is, the transfer of passengers and freight to cars on the other system. When transloading from one gauge to another, often the quantities of rolling stock are unbalanced between the two systems, leading to more idle rolling stock on one system than the other. This is obviously far from optimal, and some other schemes have been devised.\n\nVarious solutions other than transloading were conceived even in the early era of railways in Britain<ref name=\"Rolt1989\">{{Harvnb|Rolt|1989}}.</ref>{{rp|202\u2013203}} (including [[rollbock]]s, [[transporter wagon]]s, [[dual gauge]], and even [[containerization]] or [[variable gauge]] axles), but they were not implemented during the nastiest flare-up of the [[Gauge War]] in the 1840s, which resulted in horrendous spectacles of confused and wasteful transloading.<ref name=\"Rolt1989\"/>{{rp|202\u2013203}} [[L. T. C. Rolt]]'s biography of [[Isambard Kingdom Brunel]] (mastermind of the broad gauge) remarks on the apparent mysteriousness of this lack of implementation,<ref name=\"Rolt1989\"/>{{rp|202\u2013203}} but a likely explanation is that the combatants at the time were more interested in winning the Gauge War, defeating the other gauge, than in demonstrating how peaceful coexistence could be developed. Rolt states that the shocking confusion seen in an [[editorial cartoon]] of transloading chaos at [[Gloucester]] in 1843 was deliberately [[wikt:contrived#Adjective|contrived]], as later admitted by a railway [[cargo|goods]] manager, as a [[spectacle]] for a visiting parliamentary committee.<ref name=\"Rolt1989\"/>{{rp|202\u2013203}} Rolt states that the germ of the idea of [[containerization]] was known even at this time,<ref name=\"Rolt1989\"/>{{rp|202\u2013203}} which is interesting in that the full potential of containerization was not thoroughly developed until a century later, after [[World War II]].\n\nLack of a standard gauge was a significant problem in transportation in the [[Confederate States of America]] during the [[American Civil War]].\n\n===Bogie exchange and variable gauge===\n{{main|Bogie exchange|Variable gauge}}\nOne common method to avoid transshipment is to build cars to the smaller of the two systems' [[loading gauge]]s with bogies that are easily removed and replaced with other bogies at an [[Bogie exchange|interchange]] location on the border. This takes a few minutes per car, but is quicker than [[Transloading#Transloading facilities|transshipment]] of goods.\n\nA more modern and sophisticated method is to have multigauge bogies whose wheels can be [[Variable gauge|moved inward and outward]]. Normally they are locked in place, but special equipment at the border unlocks the wheels and pushes them inward or outward to the new gauge, relocking the wheels when done. This can be done as the train moves slowly over special equipment.\n\n===Dual gauge and track gauge conversion===\n{{main|Dual gauge|Track gauge conversion}}\nIn some cases, breaks of gauge are avoided by installing dual-gauge] track, either permanently or as part of a [[Track gauge conversion|changeover process]] to a single gauge.\n\n===Piggyback operation===\n{{main|Rollbock|Transporter wagon}}\nOne method of achieving interoperability between [[rolling stock]] of different gauges is to [[Piggyback (transportation)#Rail|piggyback]] stock of one gauge on special transporter wagons or even ordinary flat wagons fitted with rails. This enables rolling stock to reach workshops and other lines of the same gauge to which they are not otherwise connected. [[Transporter wagon|Piggyback]] operation by the trainload occurred as a temporary measure between [[Port Augusta railway station|Port Augusta]] and [[Marree railway station|Marree]] during [[gauge conversion]] work in the 1950s to bypass steep gradients and [[washaways]] in the [[Flinders Ranges]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southaustralianhistory.com.au/railways.htm|title=Piggyback picture}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southaustralianhistory.com.au/company.htm|title=FLINDERS RANGES RESEARCH}}</ref>\n\nNarrow-gauge railways were favoured in the underground slate quarries of [[North Wales]], as tunnels could be smaller. The [[Padarn Railway]] operated transporter wagons on their {{RailGauge|4ft|lk=on}} gauge railway, each carrying four {{RailGauge|1ft10.75in}} slate trams. When the [[Great Western Railway]] acquired one of the narrow-gauge lines in [[Blaenau Ffestiniog]], it deployed a similar type of transporter wagon to allow continued use of the quarries' existing slate wagons.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Gray |first=Adrian |date= Winter 1994 |title=G. W. R. Slate Tram Transporter Wagons |journal=British Railway Journal |issue=50 |pages=17\u201324}}</ref>\n\nTransporter wagons are most commonly used to transport narrow-gauge stock along standard-gauge lines.\n\nAt the [[Guinness brewery]] in [[Dublin]] there used to be {{RailGauge|1ft10in}} internal narrow gauge and {{RailGauge|5ft3in|lk=on}} gauge (standard gauge for Ireland), and to avoid the need for steam locomotives of both gauges the narrow-gauge engines were provided with standard-gauge converter wagons (named \"haulage trucks\"). The narrow-gauge steam locomotive was lowered into the haulage truck using a gantry, and its wheels rested on rollers, which in turn drove the haulage wagon wheels via a 3:1 reduction gear. Several of these locomotives survived into preservation, including locomotive No23 complete with haulage wagon and lifting gantry preserved at Brockham museum in 1966, and now at the [[Amberley Museum Railway]].\n\nMore rarely, standard-gauge vehicles are carried over narrow-gauge tracks using adaptor vehicles; examples include the [[Rollbock]]e transporter wagon arrangements in Germany, Austria, and the Czech Republic, and the milk transporter wagons of the [[Leek and Manifold Valley Light Railway]] in England.\n\n{{As of|2010}}, Japan is developing the [[Train on Train]] piggyback concept.\n\n===Containerisation===\n{{Main|Containerisation}} \nThe widespread use of [[Intermodal container#Rail|containers]] since the 1960s has made break of gauge less of a problem, since containers are efficiently transferred from one mode to another by suitable large [[Container crane|cranes]].\n\nIt helps if the lengths of the wagons on each gauge are the same so the containers can be transferred from one train to the other with no longitudinal movement along the trains. The different wagons should carry the same number of containers. Delays to each train depends on how many cranes can operate simultaneously.\n\nContainer cranes are relatively portable, so that if the break of gauge transshipment hub changes from time to time, the cranes can be moved around as required. [[Fork lift]] trucks can also be used.\n\nIt has been reported that, for example, when containers are shipped by a \"direct train\" from China to Europe, it is only containers, and not the railcars, which move from China's railway network to that of Kazakhstan. At the border station at [[Khorgos]], two trains (the Chinese {{RailGauge|sg|allk=on|disp=or}} one and the Kazakh {{RailGauge|1520mm|lk=on|disp=or}} one) would stand side by side at parallel tracks, while the cranes would move the containers from one train to the other in as short a time as 47 minutes.<ref name=forbes2016>{{cite|\nurl=https://www.forbes.com/sites/wadeshepard/2016/01/28/why-china-europe-silk-road-rail-transport-is-growing-fast\n|date=2016-01-28\n|title=Why The China-Europe 'Silk Road' Rail Network Is Growing Fast\n|first=Wade |last=Shepard \n|periodical=Forbes \n}}</ref>\n\n==Types==\n===Minor breaks of gauge===\nWherever there are narrow-gauge lines that connect with a standard-gauge line, there is technically a break of gauge. If the amount of traffic transferred between lines is small, this might be a small inconvenience only. In Austria and Switzerland there are numerous breaks-of-gauge between standard-gauge main lines and narrow-gauge railways.\n\nMany internal Swiss railways that operate in the more mountainous regions are {{RailGauge|1000mm|allk=on}}, and most are equipped with [[rack railway|rack]] assistance to deal with the relatively steep gradients encountered.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bueker.net/trainspotting/map.php?file=maps/switzerland/switzerland.gif|accessdate=2011-02-19|title=enlarged map}}</ref> Through running of standard-gauge trains on rack sections would not be possible, but dual-gauge track exists in many places where the gradient is relatively flat to carry standard- and metre-gauge stock. There are also some 800-mm-gauge railways which are entirely rack operated.\n\nThe effects of a minor break of gauge can be minimized by placing it at the point where a cargo must be removed from cars anyway. An example of this is the [[East Broad Top Railroad]] in the US, which had a [[coal breaker|coal wash and preparation plant]] at its break of gauge in [[Mount Union, Pennsylvania]]. The coal was unloaded from narrow-gauge cars of the EBTR, and after processing was loaded into standard-gauge cars of the [[Pennsylvania Railroad]].\n\n=== Nominal breaks of gauge ===\nThe line between Finland and Russia has a nominal break of gauge; Finnish gauge is {{RailGauge|1524mm|lk=on}} whereas [[Russian gauge]] is {{RailGauge|1520mm|lk=on}}. This does not usually prevent through-running, and in fact, such a service exists in the form of the [[Allegro (train)|Allegro]] high-speed service between Helsinki and St. Petersburg. The nominal {{convert|4|mm|abbr=on}} difference is generally within tolerance, and the present Russian gauge is actually a redefinition of the older {{RailGauge|1524mm}}.\n\nThe [[Iberian gauge]] is actually three slightly different gauges: {{RailGauge|1672mm}} in Spain, {{RailGauge|1664mm}} in Portugal, and the newer, redefined {{RailGauge|1668mm|lk=on}}. Through-running is done with vehicles having a gauge within certain tolerances. [[Indian gauge]], {{RailGauge|1676mm|lk=on}}, is also compatible with Iberian gauge, although there are no actual railway connections between the two. Despite this, old Spanish and Portuguese rolling stock have been reused in Argentina and Chile, both of which use Indian gauge.\n\nA nominal break of gauge with [[standard gauge]] exists as well: on the Hong Kong [[MTR]] network, lines owned by [[MTR Corporation]] use {{RailGauge|1432mm|lk=on}} rather than the {{RailGauge|1435mm}} employed on those owned by [[Kowloon-Canton Railway Corporation|KCR Corporation]], despite the lack of physical connections between the two networks.\n\n=== Other types of breaks ===\nA large railway may have main lines with heavy tracks, and branch lines with light track. Light locomotives and rolling stock can operate on all lines, but heavy locomotives and rolling stock can only operate on heavy track.  Heavy rolling stock might be able to operate on lighter track at reduced speed.  Light track can be upgraded to heavy track by installing heavy rails, etc., and this can be done without changing the track gauge.\n\n==Gauge conversions==\n{{Main|Track gauge conversion}}\n\n===Gauge orphan===\nWhen a main line is converted to a different gauge, branch lines can be cut off and made relatively useless, at least for freight trains, until they too are converted to the new gauge. These severed branches can be called '''gauge orphans'''.\n\n===Gauge outreach===\nThe opposite of a gauge orphan is a line of one gauge which reaches into the territory composed mainly of another gauge. Examples include five broad-gauge lines from Victoria, Australia, which crossed the border into otherwise standard-gauge New South Wales. Similarly, the standard-gauge line from Albury to Melbourne in 1962 which eliminated most transshipment at Albury, especially the need for passengers to change trains in the middle of the night.\n\nTwo Russian broad-gauge lines reach out from Ukraine, one (the [[Uzhhorod\u2013Ko\u0161ice broad-gauge track|Uzhhorod\u2013Ko\u0161ice line]]) into Slovakia to carry minerals; another (the [[Broad Gauge Metallurgy Line|Metallurgy Line]]) into Poland to carry heavy iron ore and steel products without the need for transshipment as would be the case if there were a break of gauge at the border. There are plans to extend the Slovak line to Vienna.<ref name=broad-gauge-to-wien-2010/>\n\nIn 1994, the [[Rail Baltica]] proposal emerged to build a 728&nbsp;km north\u2013south line to link European standard-gauge railways from Poland to [[Kaunas]], Lithuania, and via [[Riga]], Latvia, to [[Tallinn]], Estonia.<ref>[[Railway Gazette International]] July 2011, p 25.</ref> In the shorter term (the 2010s) it will only be built to Kaunas.\n\nThe gauge outreach from [[Kalgoorlie]] to [[Perth]] partly replaced the original narrow-gauge line, and partly rebuilt that line with better curves and gradients as double-track dual gauge. Because of lack of space at the main Perth station, standard-gauge passenger trains terminate one station short at [[East Perth railway station|East Perth]].\n\n==Other issues==\nWhile track gauge is the most important factor preventing through running between adjacent systems, other issues can also be a hindrance, including [[structure gauge]], [[loading gauge]], [[axleload]]s, [[Railway coupling|couplings]], [[Railway brake#Air versus vacuum brakes|brakes]], [[railway electrification system|electrification systems]], [[railway signal|signalling]] systems, [[multiple unit]] controls, [[Safeworking|rules and regulations]], driver certification, righthand or lefthand running, repairs (how to make and pay for repairs while rolling stock is on other railway's territory) and language. The structure gauge, loading gauge and axleload problems are solved by simply using the smaller options for through running. The general solution is often to custom-build vehicles to fit all the standards to be encountered. Trains can be built to accept four voltages, to have dual signaling systems equipment, etc. All of these solutions, however, usually result in either more expensive trains or less comfort for passengers (e.g. through less room inside the train if it has a smaller loading gauge) or \u2013 in the case of freight railways \u2013 less room for cargo, making [[double-stack rail transport|double stacking]] impossible or other negative effects.\n\n==Examples==\n\n===Europe===\n\n==== United Kingdom ====\n* [[Gloucester]] was the earliest significant break of gauge between the {{RailGauge|1435mm}} and {{RailGauge|7ft0.25in|lk=on}} systems.\n* 1864 \u2013 [[Southern Railway routes west of Salisbury#Break of Gauge|Yeovil]]\n\n====Russian gauge meeting western gauge====\n[[File:Bogie change station at Chop station Ukraine.jpg|thumb|Bogie-exchange station in Ukraine]]\n* [[Poland]], [[Slovakia]], [[Hungary]] and [[Romania]] ({{RailGauge|1435mm}}).\n:vs. Former Soviet Union countries: Russia, [[Lithuania]], [[Belarus]], [[Ukraine]],  [[Moldova]] ({{RailGauge|1520mm}}). Night trains are common, and they are often [[Bogie exchange|bogie-exchanged]].\n*Finland ({{RailGauge|1524mm}}) and Sweden ({{RailGauge|1435mm}}), between [[Tornio]] and [[Haparanda]] via a short [[dual gauge]] bridge. Freight is generally [[Transloading#Transloading facilities|transloaded]]. No passenger trains. There is also a [[SeaRail]] [[train ferry]] (with {{RailGauge|1435mm}} onboard) linking [[Turku]], Finland with [[Stockholm]], Sweden;<ref>[http://www.searail.net/en/index.html SeaRail ferry] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091226152232/http://www.searail.net/en/index.html |date=December 26, 2009 }}. Retrieved 2010-03-18</ref> the Turku terminal handles [[Dual gauge|both gauges]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.searail.net/en/services/collection_distribution.html|title=SeaRail Turku dual-gauge terminal|access-date=March 18, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724060053/http://www.searail.net/en/services/collection_distribution.html|archive-date=July 24, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*[[Bulgaria]] ({{RailGauge|1435mm}}) [[Train ferry|railroad ferries]] to Ukraine, Russia and [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] ({{RailGauge|1520mm}})\n*Germany ({{RailGauge|1435mm}}) railroad ferries (from Sassnitz with {{RailGauge|1520mm}} onboard) to Russia and Baltic States and to Finland (also from Travem\u00fcnde with {{RailGauge|1435mm}} onboard).\n*[[Turkey]] and [[Iran]] vs [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]], [[Armenia]], [[Azerbaijan]], [[Turkmenistan]]\n*While breaks of gauge are generally located near borders, the [[Uzhhorod \u2013 Ko\u0161ice broad gauge track|Uzhhorod \u2013 Ko\u0161ice line]] carrying iron ore from Ukraine extends into Slovakian territory to a steelworks near [[Ko\u0161ice]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sinfin.net/railways/world/slovakia.html|title=Railways in Slovakia}}</ref> and there are plans to extend the line further west, to [[Vienna]].<ref name=broad-gauge-to-wien-2010>{{cite web|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/nc/news/single-view/view/broad-gauge-to-wien-is-feasible-says-study.html|accessdate=2010-12-21|title=Railway Gazette: Broad gauge to Wien is feasible, says study}}</ref> See also [[Rail gauge in Slovakia]].\n*The historically first break of gauge between Russian and standard gauge was built in 1861 as dual gauge between the border stations of Eydtkuhnen, Germany (now [[Chernyshevskoye]] [[Kaliningrad Oblast]], Russia), and [[Kybartai]], then Russia, now Lithuania.\n* The 1520 Strategic Partnership seeks to harmonise the gauges of Europe-Asia.<ref>[[Railway Gazette International]] Oct 2011 p48</ref>\n\n====Iberian gauge meeting western gauge====\n*France ({{RailGauge|1435mm|disp=or}}) and Spain ({{RailGauge|1668mm|disp=or}}), for example at [[Cerb\u00e8re]] (FR) \u2013 [[Portbou]] (ES); [[Hendaye]] (FR) \u2013 [[Irun]] (ES) and [[Latour-de-Carol]]. From 2010 the [[:Category:High-speed railway lines in Spain|Spanish high-speed network]] ({{RailGauge|1435mm|disp=or}}) is connected to the French railways without a break of gauge.\n[[File:Talgo Variable Gauge Axle.jpg|thumb|[[Variable gauge axle]]s as fitted to a Spanish train designed for intercity travel to France]]\nThe earliest working example of the [[axle changing system|axle-changing system]] at the French-Spain border in 1948 had the [[axle]]s being changed at the rate of 8 wagons or 32 axles per hour.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article48647650 |title=BREAK OF GAUGE DEVICE PLEASES. |newspaper=[[The Barrier Miner]] |location=Broken Hill, NSW |date=July 16, 1951 |accessdate=November 3, 2011 |page=5 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n====Local narrow-gauge lines meeting mainlines====\n*Switzerland, see \"[[Break of gauge#Minor breaks of gauge|Minor breaks of gauge]]\" section below.\n*The Harzer Schmalspurbahn took over a standard-gauge line from Deutsche Bahn when the latter had no more use for it and regauged it to meter gauge to prevent the problems of break of gauge. Nonetheless a break of gauge (and a change of train operator) still occurs at the point where that line connects to the rest of the DB network. DB itself has no break of gauge problems as the only non-standard-gauge railway it operates is on the island of Wangerooge without any train connection to the mainland.\n\n=== North America ===\nThe [[Track gauge in the United States|United States of America]] had broad-, narrow-, and standard-gauge tracks in the 19th century, but is now almost entirely {{RailGauge|1435mm}} standard gauge. [[Narrow gauge railroads in the United States|Narrow-gauge operations]] are generally confined to isolated rail systems, with a few notable exceptions.\n*{{flagicon|Guatemala}} {{flagicon|Mexico}} A break of gauge, {{RailGauge|3ft}} to {{RailGauge|ussg}}, between [[Rail transport in Guatemala|Guatemala]] and [[Rail transport in Mexico|Mexico]] is currently closed.\n*{{flagicon|USA}} In [[Antonito, Colorado]], there is a break between the standard-gauge [[Rio Grande Scenic Railroad]] and the narrow-gauge [[Cumbres and Toltec Scenic Railroad]], billed as the [https://web.archive.org/web/20091219152629/http://www.riograndescenicrailroad.com/Tickets-and-Train-Schedules/Tickets-Routes-and-Schedules.html#tg Toltec Gorge Limited].\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[BART]] in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]] has a [[cross-platform interchange]] between the electrified {{Railgauge|1,676 mm}} broad-gauge [[Antioch\u2013SFO/Millbrae line]] and non-electrified standard gauge [[eBART]] at a transfer platform east of [[Pittsburg/Bay Point station]]. The eBART system is designed to allow the new trackage to be electrified and regauged for BART mainline trains at a later date.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gary Richards|first1=Gary Richards|title=Roadshow: eBART trains along Highway 4 could be running in 2017|url=http://www.contracostatimes.com/mr-roadshow/ci_25479165/roadshow-ebart-trains-along-highway-4-could-be|accessdate=February 24, 2015|work=Contra Costa Times|publisher=MNG Corporate|date=April 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===South America===\n*Argentina and Chile both use {{RailGauge|1676mm}} broad-gauge tracks, but [[Transandine Railway|the link railway]] uses {{RailGauge|1000mm}} narrow gauge with [[rack railway]] sections. There are two break-of-gauge stations, one at [[Los Andes, Chile]], and the other at [[Mendoza, Argentina]].\n*A break of gauge between [[Transportation in Argentina|Argentina]] and [[Transportation in Brazil|Brazil]], {{RailGauge|1435mm}} to {{RailGauge|1000mm}}\n*A break of gauge between [[Transport in Uruguay|Uruguay]] and Brazil, {{RailGauge|1435mm}} to {{RailGauge|1000mm}} at [[Santana do Livramento]].\n[[File:China - Russia Railway.jpg|thumb|A train crossing the [[China\u2013Russia border|Chinese&ndash;Russian border]], with a bogie-exchange station visible on the Russian side in the background]]\n\n===Asia===\n====China====\n[[Rail transport in China|China]] has a standard-gauge network; neighbouring countries [[Rail transport in Mongolia|Mongolia]], [[Rail transport in Russia|Russia]] and [[Qazaqstan Temir Zholy|Kazakhstan]] use {{RailGauge|1520mm}} gauge, and [[Vietnam]] mostly uses {{RailGauge|1000mm}} ([[metre gauge]]), so there are some breaks of gauge. See the [[Trans-Manchurian Railway]] (gauge changing at [[Zabaikalsk]] on the Russian side of the border), the [[Trans-Mongolian Railway]] and the [[Lanxin railway]]. The [[Yunnan\u2013Vietnam Railway]] is narrow gauge, and is connected to standard-gauge tracks both in [[Kunming]] and in [[Hekou North Railway Station|Hekou]].<ref name=\"luhao20150424\">{{cite|url=http://www.peoplerail.com/rail/show-456-224377-1.html\n|title=\u6606\u660e\u94c1\u8def\u5c40\uff1a\u56fd\u9645\u94c1\u8def\u8054\u8fd0\u5f00\u542f\u4e91\u5357\u8d27\u8fd0\u65b0\u7bc7\u7ae0 (Kunming Railway Bureau: An international railway link opens a new chapter in Yunnan's freigh transportation)\n|date=2015-04-24|last=Lu |first=Hua (\u9646\u534e)|last2=Guo|first2=Weina (\u90ed\u8587\u5a1c)}}</ref>\nThe [[Nanning]]-[[Hanoi]] line is dual gauge in Vietnam as far as Hanoi.<ref>[http://www.vr.com.vn/english/hientaihoatdong.html The length of Vietnam railway network] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100418132723/http://www.vr.com.vn/english/hientaihoatdong.html |date=April 18, 2010 }}</ref> There is currently a break of gauge at [[Dostyk]] on the Kazakh border. Kazakhstan was planning to build an additional line using standard gauge,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view/trans-kazakhstan-link-will-complete-standard-gauge-transcontinental-artery/browse/4.html\n|date=August 1, 2004 |accessdate=April 28, 2011\n|work=Railway Gazette |title=Trans-Kazakhstan link will complete standard-gauge transcontinental artery\n}}</ref> between Dostyk and [[Aktogay, East Kazakhstan Province|Aktogay]] but the scheme was abandoned.\n\n====Iran====\n[[Rail transport in Iran|Iran]], with its standard-gauge rail system, has a break of gauge with {{RailGauge|1520mm}} gauge at the borders with [[Azerbaijan]] and [[Turkmenistan]], and also with [[Rail transport in Pakistan|Pakistan's]] {{RailGauge|5ft6in}} [[Indian gauge]] at [[Zahedan]]. The break-of-gauge station at Zahedan was built outside the city, as the existing station was hemmed in by built-up areas.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/nc/news/single-view/view/closing-the-gap-from-bam-to-zahedan.html| title=Closing the gap from Bam to Zahedan| work=[[Railway Gazette International]]| first=John| last=Stubbs| date=January 1, 2007| accessdate=May 26, 2011 }}</ref>\n[[File:Free Gauge Train GCT-01 at kamogawa.jpg|thumb|The first-generation, experimental [[Gauge Change Train]] as seen in 2003]]\n\n====Japan====\nAll high-speed \"[[Shinkansen]]\" routes in Japan have been built as standard-gauge lines. A few routes, known as \"[[Super Tokky\u016b]]\", have been planned as narrow-gauge {{RailGauge|3ft6in}}, and the conventional (non-high-speed) is mostly narrow-gauge {{RailGauge|3ft6in}}, so there are some breaks of gauge and dual gauge is used in some places. Private railways often use other gauges.\n\nWhile most of the Japanese urban rail/metro lines use {{RailGauge|1067mm}} rail gauge, a considerable number of lines (including all lines of the [[Osaka Metro]]) are still using their own different gauges including {{RailGauge|762mm}}, {{RailGauge|1372mm}}, and {{RailGauge|1435mm}}.<ref>http://www.jterc.or.jp/topics/josei_shinpo3.14/5_chokutu_unten.pdf</ref> This prevented the creation of some [[through train]] services.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sc.city.kawasaki.jp/faq/contents_detail.php?frmId=12992|title=\u5ddd\u5d0e\u5e02\uff1a\u30da\u30fc\u30b8\u304c\u898b\u3064\u304b\u308a\u307e\u305b\u3093|website=sc.city.kawasaki.jp}}{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, [[Hokkaido Railway Company]] (JR Hokkaido) started working on a transporter train by trainload concept called \"[[Train on Train]]\" to carry narrow-gauge freight trains at faster speeds on standard-gauge flatcars. The [[Seikan Tunnel]] has beien converted by JR Hokkaido to dual gauge to accommodate the [[Hokkaido Shinkansen]].\n\nAn experimental variable gauge \"[[Gauge Change Train]]\" has also been tested since 1998 as a means to allow through services from high-speed standard-gauge Shinkansen lines to narrow-gauge regional lines. Its first deployment is expected to be [[Kyushu Shinkansen]] Nagasaki route.\n\n====North Korea====\nThe [[Rail transport in North Korea|North Korea]]n rail system has some breaks of gauge. Several parts of the [[Paektusan Ch'\u014fngny\u014fn Line]] on the stretch between Wiy\u014fn and Hyesan Ch'\u014fngny\u014fn are dual gauged to allow connections to the [[Paektusan Rimch'\u014fl Line]] and the [[Samjiy\u014fn Line]].<ref>http://www.cybernk.net/infoText/InfoHumanCultureDetail.aspx?mc=CC0501&sc=A33005001&tid=CC040100007874&direct=1&direct=1</ref> Also, the line connecting to the [[Trans-Siberian Railway]] from Rajin to Khasan is dual gauged for standard gauge and Russian gauge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=100&oid=112&aid=0002232229|title=\ub77c\uc9c4-\ud558\uc0b0(\ub7ec\uc2dc\uc544) \ucca0\ub3c4, 10\uc6d4 \uc911\uc21c \uccab \uc2dc\ud5d8\uc6b4\ud589|publisher=news.naver.com}}</ref>\n\n====Sakhalin====\nIn the 20th century, railroads on the entire Sakhalin used the same {{RailGauge|3ft6in}} narrow gauge as Japan, as part of it was under Japan's control when railway construction began.  One stretch of rail that used {{RailGauge|600mm}} narrow gauge was converted to match the {{RailGauge|3ft6in}} narrow gauge after Russia took control of it.\n\nStarting from the 1970s, a train ferry service was provided to connect Sakhalin and the Russia mainland, requiring bogie exchange on wagons to allow operation on the Russian mainland {{RailGauge|1520mm}} broad gauge.\n\nIn 2003, the Russian government started to convert the entire network to dual gauge with {{RailGauge|3ft6in}} and {{RailGauge|1520mm}}. Work is 70% done as of 2016, and is expected to be complete by 2018. The entire island's rolling stock is expected to be replaced by {{RailGauge|1520mm}} rolling stock by 2020, thus eliminating the break of gauge between Sakhalin and the Russian mainland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interfax-russia.ru/FarEast/news.asp?id=730322&sec=1671|title=\u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 - \u0414\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0444\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043e\u043a\u0440\u0443\u0433 -  interfax-russia.ru|website=www.interfax-russia.ru}}</ref>\n\n==== Taiwan ====\n[[File:Taiwan Railways Route Map 201301.svg|thumb|Route of THSR shown in orange; all others are operated by TRA, Taiwan]]\n\nLike Japan, [[rail transport in Taiwan]] uses the {{RailGauge|3ft6in}} gauge for the majority of its railway network, but {{RailGauge|sg}} standard gauge for its high-speed rail; however, gauge differences are less of a problem as [[Taiwan High Speed Rail]] generally uses separate rolling stocks and its own discrete railway, and at most locations runs on routes kilometres away from the conventional [[Taiwan Railways Administration]] railway network.\n\n===Africa===\n* Rail lines linked by ferries on convenient rivers or lakes. See [[Train ferry|train ferries]].\n* [[Dar es Salaam]] is one of the few places in Africa where different gauges actually meet.\n* [[Kidatu]] in [[Tanzania]] has a container transshipment facility to move freight containers between [[TAZARA Railway|TAZARA]] {{RailGauge|1067mm}} and [[Tanzania Railways Corporation]] trains {{RailGauge|1000mm}}\n* [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|D. R. Congo]] originally had both {{RailGauge|1000mm}} and {{RailGauge|3ft6in}} lines, but when these lines met in the 1950s, the {{RailGauge|1000mm}} line was converted to {{RailGauge|3ft6in}}.\n* In the rest of Africa, railways of different gauges in adjacent countries often do not actually meet, so there is no actual break of gauge.\n\n===Oceania===\n\n====Australia====\n[[File:AlburyRailwayStationPlatform.jpg|thumb|The break-of-gauge platform for the [[Sydney\u2013Melbourne railway]] at [[Albury railway station|Albury station]]; [[Standard gauge|SG]] on left; [[Broad gauge|BG]] on right.]]\n\n===== Origins =====\n\n* (1845) Evils of break of gauge and [[Royal Commission on Railway Gauges|Gauge Commission]] of UK mentioned in a South Australian newspaper.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71603492 |title=The Proposed Railroad. |newspaper=[[The South Australian]] |location=Adelaide |date=December 12, 1845 |accessdate=November 28, 2011 |page=3 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nThe then two mainland colonies originally agreed to adopt the {{RailGauge|impsg}} gauge.\n\n* [[South Australia]] (1847)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71609590 |title=Proceedings of the Legisaltive Council. |newspaper=[[The South Australian]] |location=Adelaide |date=October 8, 1847 |accessdate=November 26, 2011 |page=3 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article59769848 |title=Local Intelligence. |newspaper=[[Bell's Life in Sydney and Sporting Reviewer]] |date=December 1, 1849 |accessdate=November 27, 2011 |page=2 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n* [[New South Wales]] (1848)<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/>\n\nHowever, in 1850 New South Wales decided to change to the {{RailGauge|63in}}, or [[Irish gauge]]. The change was approved by the British government, and South Australia agreed to follow suit.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article38441575 |title=Railway Papers. |newspaper=[[South Australian Register]] |location=Adelaide |date=August 28, 1851 |accessdate=November 27, 2011 |page=3 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> However, in 1853 New South Wales unilaterally reverted to the {{RailGauge|impsg}} gauge. South Australia and [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], the latter now separated from New South Wales, protested about the broken agreement, to no avail.\n\n===== Current =====\n*[[Queensland]] ({{RailGauge|3ft6in}}) and [[New South Wales]] ({{RailGauge|impsg|disp=or}})\n*New South Wales ({{RailGauge|impsg|disp=or}}) and [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] ({{RailGauge|63in|disp=or}})\n*Southern [[South Australia]] uses broad gauge, like Victoria. Northern South Australia and southern South Australia had a number of [[narrow gauge railway|narrow-gauge]] {{RailGauge|3ft6in}} lines, leading to several break-of-gauge stations at various times including [[Hamley Bridge]], [[Terowie railway station|Terowie]], [[Peterborough railway station, South Australia|Peterborough]], [[Gladstone railway station, South Australia|Gladstone]], [[Port Pirie Junction railway station|Port Pirie Junction]], [[Port Pirie (Mary Elie Street) railway station|Port Pirie Mary Elie Street]], [[Port Augusta railway station|Port Augusta]], [[Marree railway station|Marree]], [[Wolseley, South Australia|Wolseley]] and [[Mount Gambier railway station|Mount Gambier]]. The [[Eyre Peninsula Railway]] lines have always been isolated.\n*In the latter part of the 20th century, all mainland capital cities were connected by a standard-gauge {{RailGauge|impsg}} network, leading to more breaks of gauge (or branch line closures) in states where this is not the norm\n*[[Perth]]'s railway system is narrow gauge ({{RailGauge|3ft6in|disp=or}}), while the ''[[Indian Pacific]]'' is standard gauge. The line between [[East Perth railway station|East Perth]] and [[Midland railway station, Perth|Midland]], the eastern suburban terminus, and inland to the major rail junction at [[Northam, Western Australia|Northam]] is dual gauge]. All rail east of this is standard gauge.\n*Since the 1990s, new concrete sleepers installed in the [[Adelaide]] suburban area have been [[Track gauge conversion|gauge convertible]] \n*In May 2008, agreement reached to convert the declining trafficked broad-gauge line of a [[broad gauge|BG]]/[[standard gauge|SG]] pair for 200&nbsp;km between [[Seymour railway station|Seymour]] and [[Albury railway station|Albury]] to [[double track]] standard gauge for growing interstate traffic.\n*Since the 1930s, most Victoria steam locomotives were designed for ease of conversion to standard gauge, but except for [[Victorian Railways R class|R766]], this has never happened.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railpage.com.au/f-t11303096-s180-0-asc.htm |title=It's {{sic|Offi|cal|nolink=yes}} R766 to be gauge converted & head for N.S.W \u2013 Victoria \u2013 Forums \u2013 Railpage Australia |publisher=Railpage.com.au |accessdate=15 June 2012}}</ref>\n*Note that the lines of the same gauge do not all join up, being separated by other gauges, deserts, rivers, lakes or oceans. Rolling stock is often transferred on [[Lowboy (trailer)|low-loaders]], [[Train ferry|train ferries]], [[car float]]s or even by [[ship]].\n\n==== New Zealand ====\nNew Zealand originally had small lengths of lines of {{RailGauge|3ft6in}}, {{RailGauge|impsg}} and {{RailGauge|63in}}, but quickly converted all to {{RailGauge|3ft6in}}, which better suited the sparsely populated and mountainous country.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Trains}}\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Erie Gauge War]]\n* [[Eurasian Land Bridge]]\n* [[Gauntlet track]]\n* [[Janes World Railways]] has maps that generally show breaks-of-gauge.\n* [[Piggyback (transportation)]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southaustralianhistory.com.au/fees.htm|title=Flinders Ranges Research Fees}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southaustralianhistory.com.au/email.htm|title=Flinders Ranges Research Email}}</ref>\n* [[Ramsey car-transfer apparatus]]\n* [[Track gauge conversion]]\n* [[Variable gauge axles]]\n** [[INTERGAUGE]] a form of VGA\n** [[SUW 2000]] a form of VGA\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{ cite book\n  | first = L. T. C. |last=Rolt\n  | title = Isambard Kingdom Brunel\n  | year = 1989\n  | origyear = 1957\n  | publisher = Prentice Hall Press\n  | isbn = 978-0-582-10744-1\n  | ref = harv\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061205185702/http://jwr.janes.com/public/jwr/index.shtml Jane's World Railways] (hard copy)\n*Transport and Telecommunication:[http://www.tsi.lv/Transport&Telecommunication/v71_en/art15.pdf The operation of the gauge changing facility of the new railway line Rail Baltica]{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, Jonas Jonaitis, Vol.7, No 1, 2006\n\n{{Navbox track gauge}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2016}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Break Of Gauge}}\n[[Category:Track gauges]]\n\n[[es:Cambiador de ancho]]\n", "name_user": "Kai Burghardt", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDual gauge and track gauge conversion:Spelling/grammar/punctuation/typographical correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Break_of_gauge"}
{"title_page": "Gabriel dos Santos Magalh\u00e3es", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{short description|Brazilian footballer}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Gabriel\n| image = Gabriel (LOSC).jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| fullname =  Gabriel dos Santos Magalh\u00e3es\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1997|12|19|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], Brazil\n| height = 1.90 m\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| currentclub = [[Lille OSC|Lille]]\n| clubnumber = 4\n| youthyears1 = 2012\u20132016\n| youthclubs1 = [[Ava\u00ed FC|Ava\u00ed]]\n| years1 = 2016\u20132017\n| clubs1 = [[Ava\u00ed FC|Ava\u00ed]]\n| caps1 = 21\n| goals1 = 1\n| years2 = 2017\u20132018\n| clubs2 = [[Lille OSC|Lille B]]\n| caps2 = 7\n| goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2017\u2013\n| clubs3 = [[Lille OSC|Lille]]\n| caps3 = 34\n| goals3 = 2\n| years4 = 2017\u20132018\n| clubs4 = \u2192 [[Troyes AC|Troyes]] (loan)\n| caps4 = 1\n| goals4 = 0\n| years5 = 2017\n| clubs5 = \u2192 [[Troyes AC|Troyes B]] (loan)\n| caps5 = 5\n| goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 2018\n| clubs6 = \u2192 [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]] (loan)\n| caps6 = 1\n| goals6 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2017\n| nationalteam1 = [[Brazil national under-20 football team|Brazil U20]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 3\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| pcupdate = 1 July 2019 (UTC)\n| ntupdate = 16 March 2019\n}}\n'''Gabriel dos Santos Magalh\u00e3es''' (born 19 December 1997), known as '''Gabriel''', is a Brazilian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as [[Defender (association football)|defender]] for [[Lille OSC]].\n\n==Club career==\nGabriel joined [[Ligue 1]] side [[Lille OSC]] on 31 January 2017 and later had loan spells at [[Troyes AC|Troyes]] and [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.losc.fr/joueur/losc-gabriel-dos-santos-magalhaes-2019-2020|title=Gabriel dos Santos Magalh\u00e3es|publisher= [[Lille OSC]]|accessdate=3 February 2020|language=French}}</ref> He is set to join Everton Fc!!!!!!!! CYB!\n\n==International career==\nGabriel represented Brazil at [[Brazil national under-20 football team|under-20]] level at the [[2017 South American U-20 Championship]].<ref>{{Soccerway|gabriel-dos-santos-magalhaes/433485}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Lille OSC squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gabriel dos Santos Magalh\u00e3es}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from S\u00e3o Paulo]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Brazilian footballers]]\n[[Category:Brazil under-20 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie B players]]\n[[Category:Ava\u00ed FC players]]\n[[Category:Lille OSC players]]\n[[Category:Troyes AC players]]\n[[Category:Ligue 1 players]]\n[[Category:GNK Dinamo Zagreb players]]\n[[Category:Croatian First Football League players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in France]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Croatia]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriate sportspeople in France]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriate sportspeople in Croatia]]\n\n\n{{Brazil-footy-defender-1990s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{short description|Brazilian footballer}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Gabriel\n| image = Gabriel (LOSC).jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| fullname =  Gabriel dos Santos Magalh\u00e3es\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1997|12|19|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], Brazil\n| height = 1.90 m\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| currentclub = [[Lille OSC|Lille]]\n| clubnumber = 4\n| youthyears1 = 2012\u20132016\n| youthclubs1 = [[Ava\u00ed FC|Ava\u00ed]]\n| years1 = 2016\u20132017\n| clubs1 = [[Ava\u00ed FC|Ava\u00ed]]\n| caps1 = 21\n| goals1 = 1\n| years2 = 2017\u20132018\n| clubs2 = [[Lille OSC|Lille B]]\n| caps2 = 7\n| goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2017\u2013\n| clubs3 = [[Lille OSC|Lille]]\n| caps3 = 34\n| goals3 = 2\n| years4 = 2017\u20132018\n| clubs4 = \u2192 [[Troyes AC|Troyes]] (loan)\n| caps4 = 1\n| goals4 = 0\n| years5 = 2017\n| clubs5 = \u2192 [[Troyes AC|Troyes B]] (loan)\n| caps5 = 5\n| goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 2018\n| clubs6 = \u2192 [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]] (loan)\n| caps6 = 1\n| goals6 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2017\n| nationalteam1 = [[Brazil national under-20 football team|Brazil U20]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 3\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| pcupdate = 1 July 2019 (UTC)\n| ntupdate = 16 March 2019\n}}\n'''Gabriel dos Santos Magalh\u00e3es''' (born 19 December 1997), known as '''Gabriel''', is a Brazilian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as [[Defender (association football)|defender]] for [[Lille OSC]].\n\n==Club career==\nGabriel joined [[Ligue 1]] side [[Lille OSC]] on 31 January 2017 and later had loan spells at [[Troyes AC|Troyes]] and [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.losc.fr/joueur/losc-gabriel-dos-santos-magalhaes-2019-2020|title=Gabriel dos Santos Magalh\u00e3es|publisher= [[Lille OSC]]|accessdate=3 February 2020|language=French}}</ref> he joins che\n\n==International career==\nGabriel represented Brazil at [[Brazil national under-20 football team|under-20]] level at the [[2017 South American U-20 Championship]].<ref>{{Soccerway|gabriel-dos-santos-magalhaes/433485}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Lille OSC squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gabriel dos Santos Magalh\u00e3es}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from S\u00e3o Paulo]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Brazilian footballers]]\n[[Category:Brazil under-20 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie B players]]\n[[Category:Ava\u00ed FC players]]\n[[Category:Lille OSC players]]\n[[Category:Troyes AC players]]\n[[Category:Ligue 1 players]]\n[[Category:GNK Dinamo Zagreb players]]\n[